      "name": "Does QBCC Home Warranty Insurance transfer to the buyer when I sell a newly built Brisbane home?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. QBCC Home Warranty Insurance is attached to the building work, not to the original owner. When you sell within the statutory cover period (6 years and 6 months for structural defects, 12 months for non-structural from the date of practical completion), the remaining cover automatically transfers to the buyer. The buyer can lodge their own claim with the QBCC for any covered defect that emerges during the remaining period. You should provide the buyer with the QBCC insurance certificate, the builder's contract, and any defect correspondence at settlement so they can act on the cover if needed."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What do I need to disclose about construction defects when selling a newly built home in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under the Property Law Act 2023 and the Form 2 Mandatory Seller Disclosure Statement, sellers must disclose known latent defects that are not reasonably observable on inspection. For a newly built Brisbane home this includes outstanding QBCC defect notices, unresolved builder defect rectification work, current QBCC complaints, items still inside the 12-month defects liability period under your HIA or Master Builders contract, and any structural movement or water ingress issues you are aware of. Failing to disclose a known defect exposes you to contract termination and damages claims after settlement."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long am I liable for construction defects after I sell my newly built Brisbane home?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Your liability as the seller does not end at settlement for defects you knew about and failed to disclose. The buyer can sue you for misrepresentation or breach of the disclosure regime if a known defect emerges later. Liability to the builder under QBCC home warranty insurance and the statutory builder warranty under the Domestic Building Contracts Act sits with the builder, not you, but the right to claim transfers to the buyer. The practical risk for sellers is the disclosure gap: a defect you mentioned in writing to the builder but did not tell the buyer about can become a damages claim against you years after settlement."
